Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pour a good glug of oil onto a #baking tray{} and pop in
your oven. Bring a #large saucepan{} of @water{} to the boil on high heat with a
pinch of @salt{pinch}. Peel the @potatoes{900%g}, chop them into 4cm chunks. Add the
potatoes to the boiling water and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges have
softened when you poke them with a #knife{}.

While the potatoes cook, trim the tops from the @Chantenay carrots{225%g} and halve
lengthways. Pop them on a #large baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{}. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}, @ground cumin{1%tsp} and @sugar{1}. Toss to coat the carrots
in the oil and spices and spread in a single layer at one end of the baking tray.
Carefully remove the @lamb roasting joint{450%g} from the netting (discard the
netting). Rub the @harissa paste{50%g} (use less if you don't like heat) onto the
lamb and season with salt and pepper. Place it on the other end of the carrot tray.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan and sprinkle
on half the @plain flour{3%tbsp}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato. Take your
hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single
layer, turning in the oil. Season with salt. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of
your oven for ~{45-50%minutes}, turning halfway through.

Once the potatoes have been cooking for ~{10%minutes} (or straight away if you are
cooking for 3P and 4P), roast the lamb and carrots on the middle shelf of the oven for
~{25-30%minutes} for medium rare. Add an extra ~{5%minutes} if you like your lamb more
cooked. Rest wrapped loosely in #foil{} for at least ~{10%minutes} before slicing.
Pop the @cauliflower florets{300%g} on a #smallish baking tray{} or #ovenproof dish{}
(in a single layer). Drizzle with @oil{} and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and
@pepper{}. Add the cauli to the bottom shelf of the oven to roast for the last
~{25%minutes} of potatoes' cooking time.

Meanwhile, heat a glug of oil in a #saucepan{} over medium heat, stir in the remaining
flour and cook for ~{1%minute} - you've made a roux! Gradually stir in the @water{400%ml}
and @chicken stock paste{1}, bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that may form.
Once boiling, lower the heat and simmer until the gravy has thickened to your liking,
~{15-20%minutes}. Meanwhile, grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30%g} and pop in a #bowl{}.
Add the @dukkah mix{1} to the cheese and mix together.

In the last ~{5%minutes} of cauliflower cooking time, sprinkle over the cheese and dukkah
and pop on the middle shelf for the last ~{5%minutes}. The lamb and carrots should be
out of the oven now. Once everything is cooked, thinly slice the lamb and serve with the
carrots, potatoes and cheesy cauli. Add the lamb resting juices to the gravy if you want
to make it a bit thinner. Drizzle the gravy over the meat and enjoy!